<subSubSection id="C34E48C5FF8E4021FF6024D1FB39DC00" pageId="8" pageNumber="113" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BEB1B4EFF8E4021FF6024D1FB39DC00" blockId="8.[151,1437,325,1396]" pageId="8" pageNumber="113">
<emphasis id="B920C75CFF8E4021FF6024D1FE9ADF90" bold="true" box="[199,315,398,424]" pageId="8" pageNumber="113">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species was hitherto known only from the 
<typeStatus id="54EFA5ECFF8E4021FCEB24D1FC0FDF90" box="[844,942,398,424]" pageId="8" pageNumber="113">holotype</typeStatus>
male that was fully described and illustrated by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC566BFFF8E4021FF1D24EDFE22DFF4" author="Shamshev, I. V." box="[186,387,434,460]" pageId="8" pageNumber="113" pagination="187 - 190" refId="ref6859" refString="Shamshev, I. V. (1998) Two new species of the Empis subgenus Lissempis Bezzi (Diptera: Empididae) from the Russian Far East. An International Journal of Dipterological Research, 19 (3), 187 - 190." type="journal article" year="1998">Shamshev (1998)</bibRefCitation>
. In this study, a male from 
<collectingRegion id="4990D5ACFF8E4021FD1624EDFD53DFF4" box="[689,754,434,460]" country="Russia" name="Amur" pageId="8" pageNumber="113">Amur</collectingRegion>
was examined. The specimen was partly destroyed probably by a dermestid larva on its anterior part of the head including antennae and ventral part of middle 1/3 of abdomen. Shamshev’s description is almost applicable to the examined male. The following notes include some individual variations and measurements of podites that were not mentioned in the original description.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C34E48C5FF8E4021FF60271EFE03DAA4" pageId="8" pageNumber="113" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BEB1B4EFF8E4021FF60271EFD2DDA40" blockId="8.[151,1437,325,1396]" pageId="8" pageNumber="113">
<emphasis id="B920C75CFF8E4021FF60271EFE16DC64" bold="true" box="[199,439,577,604]" pageId="8" pageNumber="113">Redescription. Male</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="136F07CBFF8E4021FE63271DFDBDDC64" box="[452,540,578,604]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1884,1908]" captionTargetBox="[157,1417,181,1859]" captionTargetId="figure-19@4.[155,1433,181,1859]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 1. Empis (Sphenempis) species. A, Empis (Sphenempis) bicoloriventris sp. nov., holotype male; B, ditto, anterodorsal aspect; C, Empis (Sphenempis) bicoloriventris sp. nov., paratype female; D, Empis (Sphenempis) amurensis, male; E, Empis (Sphenempis) oshimai sp. nov., holotype male. Scale bars = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6488266" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6488266/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="113">Fig. 1D</figureCitation>
). Body length 
<quantity id="4CACB6ABFF8E4021FD1A271DFCB0DC64" box="[701,785,578,605]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5" pageId="8" pageNumber="113" unit="mm" value="3.5">3.5 mm</quantity>
(4.0 mm supposed measurement when abdomen stretched; 
<quantity id="4CACB6ABFF8E4021FF302739FF4FDCB8" box="[151,238,614,640]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.1" pageId="8" pageNumber="113" unit="mm" value="3.1">3.1 mm</quantity>
in 
<typeStatus id="54EFA5ECFF8E4021FEB42739FEDBDCB9" box="[275,378,614,641]" pageId="8" pageNumber="113">holotype</typeStatus>
); wing length 4.0 mm (
<quantity id="4CACB6ABFF8E4021FD262739FD7BDCB8" box="[641,730,614,640]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.6" pageId="8" pageNumber="113" unit="mm" value="3.6">3.6 mm</quantity>
in 
<typeStatus id="54EFA5ECFF8E4021FD582739FCC7DCB9" box="[767,870,614,641]" pageId="8" pageNumber="113">holotype</typeStatus>
). Palpus blackish brown, brown pollinose, as long as basal thickness of labrum, slender on basal 1/2, thickened on apical 1/2, bearing several setae ventrally and long apical bristle, all black; labrum blackish towards base. Mesonotum blackish brown pollinose viewed from above, with indistinct greyish dorsomedian stripe when viewed from in front; postpronotum and postalar area polished; scutellum blackish brown pollinose; 7–10 dorsocentrals, prescutellar bristle rather short, penultimate bristle strong. Mid and hind femora yellow with brownish apical part; mid and hind tibiae yellowish brown, darker towards tip. Legs (
<figureCitation id="136F07CBFF8E4021FF782661FEFADD61" box="[223,347,830,857]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1900,1924]" captionTargetBox="[208,1380,181,1869]" captionTargetId="figure-16@9.[208,1380,181,1876]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 5. Empis (Sphenempis) amurensis, male. A, hind femur, anterior aspect; B, hind tibia, anterior aspect; C, mid femur, anterior aspect; D, mid tibia, anterior aspect; E, distal part of hind femur, anterior aspect; F, distal part of mid femur, anterior aspect; G, terminalia, lateral aspect; H, ditto, dorsal aspect; I, ditto, dorsolateral aspect. Scale bars = 0.5 mm (A–F), 0.2 mm (G), 0.1 mm (H, I)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6488276" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6488276/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="113">Figs 5A–F</figureCitation>
) thicker than in 
<taxonomicName id="4C5460CDFF8E4021FDB92661FD62DD60" authority="Saigusa, 2022" authorityName="Saigusa" authorityYear="2022" box="[542,707,830,856]" class="Insecta" family="Empididae" genus="Empis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="113" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bicoloriventris" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B920C75CFF8E4021FDB92661FD62DD60" box="[542,707,830,856]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="113">bicoloriventris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B920C75CFF8E4021FD6A2661FC88DD60" bold="true" box="[717,809,830,856]" pageId="8" pageNumber="113">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A2137A27FF8E4021FD6A2661FC88DD60" box="[717,809,830,856]" pageId="8" pageNumber="113" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
; mid femur thick, 9.5 times as long as thick with 5–6 anteroventral and 4 posteroventral spines. Hind femur thick, 10 times as long as thick, with strong anterior preapical bristle almost as strong as and longer than longest anteroventral spines; 6 anteroventral spines and 2 posteroventral spines; hind tibia with long dorsal bristles 2 times as long as hind tibia thickness. Wing (
<figureCitation id="136F07CBFF8E4021FB1326F5FAAFDDFC" box="[1204,1294,938,964]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1114,1138]" captionTargetBox="[156,1431,309,1083]" captionTargetId="figure-73@6.[156,1431,309,1091]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 3. Wings of Empis species. A, Empis (Sphenempis) bicoloriventris sp. nov., paratype male from Okinawa-jima; B, Empis (Sphenempis) amurensis, male; C, Empis (Sphenempis) oshimai sp. nov., paratype male; D, Empis (Lissempis) nigritarsis, female; E, Empis sp. close to E. kasparyani, male from Kagoshima, Kyushu; F, Empis leptogastra Loew, male. Scale bars = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6488272" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6488272/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="113">Fig. 3B</figureCitation>
) wider than 
<taxonomicName id="4C5460CDFF8E4021FF302691FE9DDDD0" authority="Saigusa, 2022" authorityName="Saigusa" authorityYear="2022" box="[151,316,974,1000]" class="Insecta" family="Empididae" genus="Empis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="113" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bicoloriventris" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B920C75CFF8E4021FF302691FE9DDDD0" box="[151,316,974,1000]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="113">bicoloriventris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B920C75CFF8E4021FEE32691FE3EDDD0" bold="true" box="[324,415,974,1000]" pageId="8" pageNumber="113">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A2137A27FF8E4021FEE32691FE3EDDD0" box="[324,415,974,1000]" pageId="8" pageNumber="113" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, about 3.2 times as long as wide: cell r 
<subScript id="17D0190BFF8E4021FCF926BFFCD6DDD6" attach="left" box="[862,887,992,1006]" fontSize="6" pageId="8" pageNumber="113">2+3</subScript>
almost as wide as cell r 
<subScript id="17D0190BFF8E4021FB2D26BFFB05DDD6" attach="left" box="[1162,1188,992,1006]" fontSize="6" pageId="8" pageNumber="113">4+5</subScript>
at level of tip of vein R 
<subScript id="17D0190BFF8E4021FF0D215BFF62DA2A" attach="left" box="[170,195,1028,1042]" fontSize="6" pageId="8" pageNumber="113">2+3</subScript>
; discal cell 0.52 times as long as vein M 
<subScript id="17D0190BFF8E4021FD34215BFD3ADA2A" attach="left" box="[659,667,1028,1042]" fontSize="6" pageId="8" pageNumber="113">1</subScript>
; axillary lobe narrow, widest at middle, with evenly curved margin; angle of fork of R 
<subScript id="17D0190BFF8E4021FEC12177FE21DA0E" attach="left" box="[358,384,1064,1078]" fontSize="6" pageId="8" pageNumber="113">4+5</subScript>
about 80°. Abdomen entirely polished blackish brown to black, bearing black longish setae. Terminalia (
<figureCitation id="136F07CBFF8E4021FE862165FE3ADA6D" box="[289,411,1082,1109]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1900,1924]" captionTargetBox="[208,1380,181,1869]" captionTargetId="figure-16@9.[208,1380,181,1876]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 5. Empis (Sphenempis) amurensis, male. A, hind femur, anterior aspect; B, hind tibia, anterior aspect; C, mid femur, anterior aspect; D, mid tibia, anterior aspect; E, distal part of hind femur, anterior aspect; F, distal part of mid femur, anterior aspect; G, terminalia, lateral aspect; H, ditto, dorsal aspect; I, ditto, dorsolateral aspect. Scale bars = 0.5 mm (A–F), 0.2 mm (G), 0.1 mm (H, I)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6488276" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6488276/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="113">Figs 5G–I</figureCitation>
): Palm-like process with two fairly long finger-like lobes, with weakly rounded proximal swelling; cercus distinctly raised posteriorly.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BEB1B4EFF8E4021FF6021DDFE03DAA4" blockId="8.[151,1437,325,1396]" box="[199,418,1154,1180]" pageId="8" pageNumber="113">
<emphasis id="B920C75CFF8E4021FF6021DDFE84DAA4" bold="true" box="[199,293,1154,1180]" pageId="8" pageNumber="113">Female.</emphasis>
Unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
